      "passage": "As cities grow larger, feeding their populations has become a significant challenge. One idea gaining attention is the rooftop farm: a garden built on top of a building, where vegetables and herbs are grown close to the people who eat them.\n\nSupporters argue that rooftop farms could contribute to a city's food supply in several ways. First, growing food locally reduces the distance it must travel, which lowers pollution from trucks. Second, the plants help enhance air quality and keep buildings cooler in summer. Some farms even generate a small income by selling produce to nearby restaurants.\n\nHowever, rooftop farming is not simple to implement. Roofs must be strong enough to hold soil, water, and workers. Watering systems can be expensive, and not every building receives enough sunlight. If these problems are ignored, the consequence may be a project that costs more than it produces.\n\nResearchers note that the benefits accumulate slowly. A single rooftop farm will not solve a city's food problems. But if many buildings adopt the idea, the combined effect could be meaningful.\n\nFor now, rooftop farms remain a promising experiment rather than a complete solution — a reminder that even good ideas require careful planning to succeed.",
