      "title": "Why Do We Dream?",
      "passage": "For as long as people have slept, they have wondered about the strange worlds they visit while dreaming. Ancient cultures often treated dreams as messages from the gods, while today scientists study them in sleep laboratories. Yet despite all this attention, no one can say with complete certainty why we dream. What researchers can offer instead is a set of competing theories, each supported by some evidence.\n\nOne widely discussed idea is that dreams help the brain process emotions. During an ordinary day we experience many feelings, and we do not always deal with them fully while we are awake. According to this theory, the sleeping brain returns to these unfinished emotions, replaying and reorganising them. This may be why a worry that seemed enormous late at night can feel far more manageable the following morning.\n\nA second theory connects dreaming with memory. While we sleep, the brain appears to review the information gathered during the day, strengthening the connections that matter and discarding those that do not. Dreams, in this view, are a side effect of that nightly sorting process. The idea fits a familiar piece of advice: students who sleep well after studying tend to remember more than those who stay awake all night.\n\nNot every scientist is convinced that dreams mean anything at all. Some argue that they are simply random signals produced by a resting brain, which then invents a loose story to make sense of the noise. Supporters of this view point out that many dreams are confused, illogical, and impossible to interpret. Whatever the answer finally turns out to be, dreams remain one of the most ordinary and yet most mysterious parts of human life.",
