      "title": "The Hidden Cost of Fast Fashion",
      "passage": "Walk into almost any shopping centre today and you will find clothing that is cheaper, more fashionable, and more quickly produced than ever before. This is the world of fast fashion: new styles appear in the shops every few weeks, prices stay remarkably low, and many shoppers buy far more than they could ever actually wear. The system seems to benefit everyone — until we look more closely at what those low prices really hide.\n\nThe first hidden cost is environmental. Producing clothing on this enormous scale uses vast quantities of water and energy, and the dyeing of fabrics pollutes rivers in many parts of the world. Worse still, garments are now thrown away faster than ever before. When unwanted clothes reach landfill sites, the synthetic fibres in them can take decades, or even centuries, to break down. The fashion industry has quietly become one of the planet's largest sources of waste.\n\nThere is also a human cost that shoppers rarely see. To keep prices as low as possible, some brands depend on factories where workers labour for long hours, earn very little, and face conditions that would be unacceptable elsewhere. Because these workers live far from the shops that sell the clothes, it is easy for customers to forget that a real person, somewhere, paid a price for a cheap shirt.\n\nRecognising these problems does not mean we must stop buying clothes altogether, which would be neither realistic nor fair to the people the industry employs. The more useful response is to buy more thoughtfully. Choosing fewer but better-made items, repairing clothes instead of replacing them, and supporting brands that treat workers and the planet with respect can all make a genuine difference. In the end, the question is not only whether we can afford fast fashion, but whether the planet, and the people who make our clothes, can afford it too.",
