      "title": "The Paradox of Choice",
      "passage": "Modern life offers more choices than any previous generation could have imagined. A single supermarket may stock forty kinds of breakfast cereal, while an online store can present thousands of options for something as ordinary as a pair of headphones. We generally treat this abundance as a clear sign of progress, assuming without question that more choice must always mean greater freedom and greater happiness. Psychologists, however, have begun to challenge that comfortable assumption.\n\nIn principle, a wider range of options should benefit everyone. With more to choose from, each person ought to be able to find the product, the job, or the lifestyle that suits them most precisely. A shop that offers only two kinds of shoes cannot satisfy as many people as one that offers two hundred. On paper, then, choice and satisfaction should rise together, hand in hand.\n\nIn practice, the relationship is far more complicated. Once the number of options grows beyond a certain point, many people begin to feel not liberated but overwhelmed. Faced with dozens of broadly similar alternatives, they hesitate, postpone the decision, or occasionally avoid choosing at all. Researchers have even found that shoppers shown a huge display of products are sometimes less likely to buy anything than those offered a small, manageable selection. The very abundance that was meant to help can quietly paralyse.\n\nThe difficulty does not end once a decision is finally made. When only one or two options were available, we rarely waste energy wondering about the path we did not take. But when we have rejected twenty attractive alternatives, it becomes tempting to imagine that one of them might have suited us better. This lingering sense of doubt can slowly erode the satisfaction we ought to feel, leaving us faintly disappointed with a perfectly good choice.\n\nNone of this means that choice is a bad thing. The freedom to choose remains one of the genuine privileges of modern life, and few of us would willingly return to a world of empty shelves. The point is subtler. Beyond a certain threshold, each additional option adds less and less real value, while quietly increasing both the mental effort required and the risk of later regret. Recognising this paradox will not make our decisions for us, but it may encourage us to set sensible limits, simplify where we can, and feel more content with the good choices we have already made.",
