      "category": "science",
      "title": "Why Time Seems to Speed Up as We Age",
      "passage": "Ask almost anyone over the age of thirty, and they will describe the same strange sensation: time appears to accelerate as the years go by. The long, lazy summers of childhood seem to have lasted forever, yet entire years now vanish almost without notice. A birthday arrives, and it feels as though the previous one was only weeks ago. Curiously, a year is always exactly the same length — 365 days, no more and no less. What changes is not time itself, but the way our minds measure it. For something so universal, the feeling is surprisingly difficult to explain, and researchers have proposed several competing ideas.\n\nThe simplest explanation is mathematical, and it is sometimes called the proportional theory. To a five-year-old child, a single year represents one fifth of everything they have ever lived — an immense, unforgettable stretch of time. To a fifty-year-old, that very same year is merely one part in fifty of their experience. Because each new year forms a smaller and smaller fraction of the life already lived, it naturally feels shorter by comparison. By this logic, the months should appear to shrink steadily as we grow older, which is more or less what most people report.\n\nPsychologists, however, offer a second and complementary explanation, one based on memory rather than mathematics. Our sense of how much time has passed depends heavily on how many distinct experiences we can recall from a given period. Childhood and adolescence are crowded with novelty: a first day at school, a first journey abroad, a first close friendship, a first taste of independence. These vivid, first-time experiences leave deep marks in the memory and make the period feel densely packed, and therefore long. Adult life, by contrast, often settles into comfortable routine. One ordinary working week resembles the next so closely that the brain stores few separate memories, and in looking back we find little to hold on to. The months blur together, and the year seems to have quietly slipped away.\n\nNot everyone is convinced that either theory tells the whole story. Some scientists argue that our perception of time is also shaped by attention and emotion: a frightening or exciting moment can stretch in the memory, while a dull afternoon shrinks to almost nothing. Others point out that the feeling varies from one person to another, which suggests there may be no single, universal cause at all.\n\nWhatever the true explanation, the memory theory in particular offers a hopeful and practical lesson. If routine makes time feel short, then deliberately seeking out novelty may help to reverse the effect. Learning an unfamiliar skill, travelling somewhere new, or simply breaking a daily habit all create fresh memories that, in a sense, expand our experience of time. We cannot slow the clock on the wall, but by filling our years with new and meaningful moments, we may at least make them feel fuller — and, perhaps, longer.",
