      "title": "The Rise of Urban Farming",
      "passage": "In cities around the world, a quiet change is taking place on rooftops, balconies, and empty plots of land. Urban farming — growing food within a city rather than in the countryside — is becoming increasingly popular, and for several practical reasons.\n\nThe first is freshness. Vegetables grown in the city can reach local markets within hours, rather than travelling long distances by truck. This not only improves their taste but also reduces the fuel used in transport.\n\nUrban farms also make use of space that would otherwise be wasted. A flat rooftop, for example, can be turned into a productive garden that helps cool the building below. Some restaurants now grow herbs on their own roofs, picking them only minutes before they are served.\n\nThere are social benefits too. Community gardens, where neighbours share a plot of land, bring people together and give city children a chance to see how food is grown. For many families, this connection to nature is a welcome break from busy urban life.\n\nOf course, urban farming cannot replace traditional agriculture; cities simply do not have enough space to feed everyone. But as a supplement, it offers fresher food, greener buildings, and stronger communities — a small but meaningful step toward more sustainable cities.",
