      "title": "Should Students Use Smartphones in Class?",
      "passage": "Few topics divide teachers and students as sharply as the use of smartphones in the classroom. Some schools ban them completely, while others encourage their use as learning tools. So which side is right?\n\nThose who oppose phones in class make a strong case. Smartphones are a constant source of distraction: a single notification can pull a student's attention away from a lesson, and research suggests that even having a phone on the desk can reduce concentration. There is also the temptation to cheat, or simply to scroll through social media instead of listening.\n\nSupporters, however, argue that banning phones ignores their real value. A smartphone can be a dictionary, a calculator, and a gateway to information all at once. Used well, it allows students to look up unfamiliar words, take part in online quizzes, and learn at their own pace.\n\nThe truth, perhaps, lies somewhere in between. The problem is not the device itself but how it is used. Rather than banning phones outright, schools might teach students to use them responsibly — switching them to silent during explanations, and taking them out only for specific tasks. In a world where technology is everywhere, learning to manage it may prove more useful than learning to live without it.",
