      "title": "Should Single-Use Plastics Be Banned?",
      "passage": "Plastic bags, straws, bottles, and food containers have become part of daily life. They are cheap, light, and convenient — and they are almost everywhere. In recent years, however, many governments have begun to ban or tax single-use plastics: items that are designed to be thrown away after only one use. Supporters say such measures are long overdue, while critics argue that they cause more problems than they solve. So which side has the stronger case?\n\nThose in favour of banning single-use plastics point to the enormous damage these products cause. The great majority of them are never recycled. Instead, they end up in rivers, oceans, and landfills, where they can take hundreds of years to break down. Along the way, they harm wildlife: sea turtles mistake floating plastic bags for jellyfish, and seabirds feed tiny plastic fragments to their chicks. Every year, millions of tonnes of plastic flow into the sea, and much of it never truly disappears — it only breaks into smaller and smaller pieces. By cutting plastic off at the source, supporters argue, a ban deals with the problem before it begins, rather than relying on recycling systems that frequently fail.\n\nOpponents, however, raise a number of practical concerns. Plastic is cheap, light, and hygienic, and for some people it is genuinely hard to replace. Disabled people, for instance, may depend on flexible plastic straws that stiff paper ones cannot match. Small businesses worry about the rising cost of alternatives, and some scientists point out that producing paper or cotton bags can actually use more water and energy than making plastic ones. A poorly designed ban, they warn, may simply move the harm somewhere else rather than removing it.\n\nBoth sides make fair points, and the issue is rarely as simple as it first appears. A ban that removes plastic straws but ignores the far larger problem of plastic packaging may achieve very little in practice. On the other hand, doing nothing at all is clearly not a serious option, given the sheer scale of plastic pollution today. The wisest path may lie in careful design: banning the most harmful and least necessary items first, while offering affordable alternatives and protecting the small number of people who truly need certain plastic products.\n\nIn the end, single-use plastics offer a useful example of how environmental decisions are seldom black and white. Banning them can bring real and lasting benefits, but only if it is done thoughtfully, with proper attention to cost, fairness, and the wider picture. The aim, after all, is not merely to be seen to be doing something, but to make a genuine difference to the planet that we all share.",
